metadata.name: Pepe's Family #75
metadata.description:
Pepes are here! You can adopt them by chance. Attention! Watch your behavior! They are in different styles and social levels. So, some of them are really aggressive and hostile. It may take times to be friend with some of them. Try your best! On the other side, some of them are really friendly & easy going. It depends on your chance! 
 
There are 6 traits (42 layers): 
Background: 7 layers 
Skin: 7 layers 
Mouth: 4 layers
Eyes & Glasses: 9 layers
Head Accessories: 11 layers 
Necklace: 4 layers

metadata.name: Paradise Bottle #31
metadata.description:
In this project I tried to find some kind of an extraordinary design for a typical bottle of water, one that is more colorful and has different shapes.

Nothing better than mixing AI + Generative art.

I hope you like it! :D

metadata.name: Wonderscapes #105
metadata.description:
In the infinite abyss of wondering there are some random moments of beauty which will stay in memory and at the end they will remind us that exploration and efforts were not in vain.

This artwork is rendered in real-time using custom webStyleGAN model (~25mb) which was trained on a dataset of about 5000 wonderscapes generated by DALL-E from OpenAI.

In addition to the main generative model, there is a CNN classifier model that filters the rendered images by predicting similarity to landscapes (this may take some time with each generation).

On top of the image generated by the neural network, there is a processing script that converts the value of each pixel into a colored ASCII character, the final result is a 64x64 vector grid with 4096 text symbols.

Controls:
- Press [s] to save the high resolution image

metadata.name: Nature Force #59
metadata.description:
Nature forces
It is the expression of mother nature in static and textured forms.

Central piece represent the sun radiation, the sea stregth and the atoms complexity.
This piece manifests in 3 pieces, swirl, radiant and atom. Compose of 22 layers, that 
follow golden ratio 1,1618. All 3 have 75% chance to appear !

Canvas is composed of 3 diffents effects, first Wind force showing their blades, 
second Mandala represent plants symmetry demonstrated in various manifestations in nature 
and last one Liquify bringing the sea movements and their inclusion of other elements in them.

Finally, the picture involves all this power, keeping the centerpiece highlighted, 
but it still has its representativeness. 
Bringing in the first point, Thunder, the electrical forces to compose,
 in second, the union of two elements becoming the Booger density and 
finally bringing the technology to the context that everything is part of the 
nature, formation of pixel.

Nature sounds can change between sign wind, waterfalls and thunder rain.

You have 1% chance to mint nature power, 
this feature means movement to your piece, can be 0.00 or 100.00.

You have 1,5% chance to mint 3x feature simple, on piece, canvas and picture. 
Simple means no piece, clear canvas and picture, but if have that lucky, 
next drop will be free.


Press 'S' to print in full screen view and full quality '4k'. 

Features : 
Nature Life Power have 1% chance to be on.
Central piece, swirl,atom and radiant have 75% chance to appear.
Full Simple 1,5% chance to combine.(Simple + Simple + Simple)
Full Storm 0,4% chance to combine. (Atom + Thunder + Mandala + Thunder rain)
Full Water 0,4% chance to combine.( Swirl + Liquify + Booger + Waterfalls)
Full Tornado 0,4% chance to combine.(Radiant + Wind + Pixel + Sign wind)

metadata.name: Glomularus #149
metadata.description:
Glomularus is an exploration in generative, artificial life forms. The project is an extension of my Protobyte series, begun in 2004.

Driven by Verlet icosahedra and responsive tendrils, Glomulari live in a spherical virtual ecosystem (V-eco) enhanced through user interaction.

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
  drag -> camera rotation
  drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
  scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
  1-9: add acceleration
  -, +: reduce | increase V-eco sphere radius
  f, g: reduce | increase fog
  p: screen capture

Tip:
To decrease creature acceleration, reduce V-eco sphere radius

Note:
Please post your favorite Glomularus screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: BRUTALIST MOVEMENT #211
metadata.description:
Inspired and fascinated by Brutalism, Modernism and Bauhaus, I've started to explore the deeper connections of architecture using pixel art in a clean, minimalistic and unique way.

The BRUTALIST MOVEMENT project represents the next step in this process. It's an animated generative experiment that focuses on finding the simplest and fewest components that - when generated randomly - always create structures resembling buildings: from small modern houses through industrial facilities to gigantic brutalist monuments.

This resulted in 4 main components: Base, Extension, Gap and Window. These entities are used randomly to create Blocks that form the final structure. 
The whole process is also strictly accompanied by 4 distinct components to hold colors and to be set by randomly chosen palettes: Sky, Sun, Shadow, Window.

Features consist of a mixture of the above components.

The project is animated to show how the buildings come to life. It's also a nice way to show what's going on in the background, because from time to time a bigger block would surely hide interesting smaller ones :) 

Press these keys:
's' - to download a larger resolution PNG
'n' - to shuffle through the 'depth' of Blocks, aka placing them from front to back and vice versa. This is a nice feature to show structures hidden by others and also a cool way to create iterations inside the iteration - sub-iterations - we can say :)
'r' - to reset the Blocks' depths to default

Please note:
Everything you see is generated, animated and drawn real-time. No layered transparent PNGs, PFP or similar!

Have fun and inspiration!


@cloudnoise © 2022

☁︎

Created with P5.js library.

metadata.name: Across Paper Stones #136
metadata.description:
Wherever you want to go, you'll find a path to take you there.

Each tile is made up of two deformed rectangles. One is drawn with a drifting, fragmented outline.

Over thirty color palettes are shuffled together on each output, helping form slight edges between groups.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.
